abstract: Michael Bloomberg, the billionaire media mogul who is seeking the Democratic nomination for U.S. president, on Saturday opened campaign offices in Pennsylvania, Michigan and Wisconsin, three battleground states crucial in next year's election.
snippet: Michael Bloomberg, the billionaire media mogul who is seeking the Democratic nomination for U.S. president, on Saturday opened campaign offices in Pennsylvania, Michigan and Wisconsin, three battleground states crucial in next year's election.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Michael Bloomberg, the billionaire media mogul who is seeking the Democratic nomination for U.S. president, on Saturday opened campaign offices in Pennsylvania, Michigan and Wisconsin, three battleground states crucial in next year's election.
headline_main: Democrat Bloomberg Opens Campaign Offices in Three Battleground States
headline_print_headline: Democrat Bloomberg Opens Campaign Offices in Three Battleground States

abstract: Richard North Patterson wrote best-selling novels about presidents, until he decided that the political moment was too strange to make anything up.
snippet: Richard North Patterson wrote best-selling novels about presidents, until he decided that the political moment was too strange to make anything up.
lead_paragraph: WEST TISBURY, Mass. — Over four decades and nearly two dozen thrillers, the novelist Richard North Patterson has used current events as scaffolding for his imagination. Late-stage abortion, conflict in the Middle East, genocide in Africa, gun control, the death penalty — the thornier the issue, the better.

abstract: Latinos in Arizona can show how it’s done.
snippet: Latinos in Arizona can show how it’s done.
lead_paragraph: PHOENIX — First there were seven. Then 50. Then thousands of people, mostly Latino and many undocumented, who held a vigil on the lawn outside of the Arizona State Capitol in the spring of 2010, praying that Gov. Jan Brewer would not sign an anti-immigrant bill, the most punitive in generations, which had sailed through the Republican-controlled Legislature.

headline_main: How to Turn Anger and Fear Into Political Power
byline_original: By Alejandra Gomez and Tomás Robles Jr

abstract: The Communist Party is reviving traditional beliefs for political gain — while cracking down on some faiths.
snippet: The Communist Party is reviving traditional beliefs for political gain — while cracking down on some faiths.
lead_paragraph: BEIJING — In the northern suburbs of this city is a small temple to a Chinese folk deity, Lord Guan, a famous warrior deified more than a millennium ago. Renovated five years ago at the government’s expense, the temple is used by a group of retirees who run pilgrimages to a holy mountain, schoolchildren who come to learn traditional culture and a Taoist priest who preaches to wealthy urbanites about the traditional values of ancient China.

abstract: The head of Argentina´s new cabinet under President Alberto Fernandez said on Saturday that the government would make a series of belt-tightening "public spending adjustments," just hours after the country´s senate gave final legislative approval to an emergency economic reform package touted by Fernandez as the country's best chance at sparking growth.
snippet: The head of Argentina´s new cabinet under President Alberto Fernandez said on Saturday that the government would make a series of belt-tightening "public spending adjustments," just hours after the country´s senate gave final legislative approval ...
lead_paragraph: BUENOS AIRES — The head of Argentina´s new cabinet under President Alberto Fernandez said on Saturday that the government would make a series of belt-tightening "public spending adjustments," just hours after the country´s senate gave final legislative approval to an emergency economic reform package touted by Fernandez as the country's best chance at sparking growth.
headline_main: Argentina´s Cabinet Chief Unveils Public Service Belt-Tightening Measures
headline_print_headline: Argentina´s Cabinet Chief Unveils Public Service Belt-Tightening Measures

abstract: The Christian past shapes the secular present. Does it matter?
snippet: The Christian past shapes the secular present. Does it matter?
lead_paragraph: In early November, a study published in the journal Science claimed to trace the whole social course of modernity — the decline of clan and tribe, the turn to nuclear families, the rise of individualism — back to Roman Catholicism’s opposition to incest.

abstract: Philip Yancey, an evangelical Christian writer, responds to my questions, and my doubts.
snippet: Philip Yancey, an evangelical Christian writer, responds to my questions, and my doubts.
lead_paragraph: Welcome to the latest in my occasional series of conversations about Christianity. Here’s my interview, edited for space, with Philip Yancey, an evangelical Christian writer who has more than 15 million books in print in more than 50 languages.

headline_main: Was the Virgin Mary a Virgin? Does It Matter?
headline_print_headline: Was Mary a Virgin? Does it Matter?

abstract: We’ve lost our ability to take comfort in small things.
snippet: We’ve lost our ability to take comfort in small things.
lead_paragraph: Recently I have been forced to think a bit about happiness. It’s not something I’ve done before. I have been too busy living. But when an interview with me appeared in The Sunday Times under the headline “Why ‘This Is Happiness’ Author Niall Williams Is Happily Out of Step,” I began to realize that it was not just me but the idea of happiness itself that was out of step with the times, and that it required some mental adjusting, not to say daring, to say aloud the title of my novel.

abstract: U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo on Saturday said Russia and China had blood on their hands after the two countries used a veto of a U.N. Security Council resolution to block cross-border aid deliveries from Turkey and Iraq to millions of Syrian civilians.
snippet: U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo on Saturday said Russia and China had blood on their hands after the two countries used a veto of a U.N. Security Council resolution to block cross-border aid deliveries from Turkey and Iraq to millions of Syria...
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo on Saturday said Russia and China had blood on their hands after the two countries used a veto of a U.N. Security Council resolution to block cross-border aid deliveries from Turkey and Iraq to millions of Syrian civilians.
headline_main: Russia, China Have Blood on Their Hands After Veto on Syria Cross-Border Aid: Pompeo
headline_print_headline: Russia, China Have Blood on Their Hands After Veto on Syria Cross-Border Aid: Pompeo

abstract: Five people suspected of burning down four mosques in Ethiopia's Amhara region were arrested on Saturday, a regional spokesman said, as rising inter-communal and ethnic violence threatens political reforms initiated by Prime Minister Abiy Ahmed.
snippet: Five people suspected of burning down four mosques in Ethiopia's Amhara region were arrested on Saturday, a regional spokesman said, as rising inter-communal and ethnic violence threatens political reforms initiated by Prime Minister Abiy Ahmed.
lead_paragraph: ADDIS ABABA — Five people suspected of burning down four mosques in Ethiopia's Amhara region were arrested on Saturday, a regional spokesman said, as rising inter-communal and ethnic violence threatens political reforms initiated by Prime Minister Abiy Ahmed.
headline_main: Five Arrested in Ethiopia for Arson Attack on Mosques: State Government
headline_print_headline: Five Arrested in Ethiopia for Arson Attack on Mosques: State Government
